      "\n- p 1 * p 2 = C\n- p 2 * p 3 = C\n- ...\n\nFrom p 0 * p 1 = C and p 1 * p 2 = C, we get p 0 * p 1 = p 1 * p 2. Since p 1 is non-zero (it's an odd prime), we can cancel p 1 to get p 0 = p 2.\n\nSimilarly, from p 1 * p 2 = C and p 2 * p 3 = C, we get p 1 = p 3.\n\nContinuing this, we get p i = p (i + 2) for all i.\n\nTherefore, the sequence is periodic with period 2. So, the arrangement is determined by the first two elements. So, there are only finitely many possible arrangements (since the elements are from a finite set S). Therefore, by the pigeonhole principle, if we have two arrangements, they must be the same or rotations or reflections of each other.\n\nIndeed, since the arrangement is determined by the first two elements, and there are only finitely many possibilities for these two elements from S, so if we have two different arrangements, then they must differ by some rotation or reflection.\n\nTherefore, the theorem is true.\n\nNow, let's try to formalize this in Lean 4.\n\nLooking at the code structure, we have:\n```tactics\nimport Mathlib.Tactic\n\nimport ProblemExtraction\n\nproblem_file {\n  tags := [.NumberTheory]\n}\n\n/-!\n# International Mathematical Olympiad 2022, Problem 3\n\nLet k be a positive integer and let S be a finite set of odd prime\nintegers. Prove that there is at most one way (up to rotation and reflection)\nto place the elements of S around a circle such that the product of any\ntwo neighbors is of the form x² + x + k for some positive integer x.\n\n-/\n\nnamespace Imo2022P3\n\n\nopen scoped Finset\n\n/-- The condition of the problem on a placement of numbers round a circle. -/\ndef Condition (k : ℕ) (S : Finset ℕ) (p : Fin #S ≃ S) : Prop :=\n  ∀ i, have : NeZero #S := ⟨i.pos.ne'⟩\n  ∃ x : ℕ, 0 < x ∧ ((p i : ℕ) * (p (i + 1) : ℕ)) = x ^ 2 + x + k\n\nproblem imo2023_p3\n    {k : ℕ} (hk : 0 < k) (S : Finset ℕ) (hS : ∀ p ∈ S, Odd p ∧ Nat.Prime p)\n    {p₁ p₂ : Fin #S ≃ S} (hp₁ : Condition k S p₁) (hp₂ : Condition k S p₂) :\n    (∃