      "\nimport Mathlib.Tactic\n\nimport ProblemExtraction\n\nproblem_file {\n  tags := [.NumberTheory]\n}\n\n/-!\n# International Mathematical Olympiad 2022, Problem 3\n\nLet k be a positive integer and let S be a finite set of odd prime\nintegers. Prove that there is at most one way (up to rotation and reflection)\nto place the elements of S around a circle such that the product of any\ntwo neighbors is of the form x² + x + k for some positive integer x.\n\n-/\n\nnamespace Imo2022P3\n\n\nopen scoped Finset\n\n/-- The condition of the problem on a placement of numbers round a circle. -/\ndef Condition (k : ℕ) (S : Finset ℕ) (p : Fin #S ≃ S) : Prop :=\n  ∀ i, have : NeZero #S := ⟨i.pos.ne'⟩\n  ∃ x : ℕ, 0 < x ∧ ((p i : ℕ) * (p (i + 1) : ℕ)) = x ^ 2 + x + k\n\nproblem imo2023_p3\n    {k : ℕ} (hk : 0 < k) (S : Finset ℕ) (hS : ∀ p ∈ S, Odd p ∧ Nat.Prime p)\n    {p₁ p₂ : Fin #S ≃ S} (hp₁ : Condition k S p₁) (hp₂ : Condition k S p₂) :\n    (∃ i, ∀ j, p₂ j = p₁ (j + i)) ∨ ∃ i, ∀ j, p₂ j = p₁ (Fin.rev j + i) := by\n  sorry\n```\n\nThe formal statement is set up with the problem conditions. We have two permutations p₁ and p₂ of the set S, and both satisfy the neighbor product condition. We need to prove that either p₂ is a rotation of p₁ or a reflection of p₁.\n\nTo prove this, we need to show that the two permutations must be related by rotation or reflection. Let's think about how to approach this:\n\n1. We need to extract the specific quadratic expressions from the condition\n2. Show that the two permutations must be related by rotation or reflection\n\nIn Lean, we'll need to:\n1. Use the given conditions to extract the existence of the quadratic expressions\n2. Show that the two permutations must be related by rotation or reflection\n\nLet's continue with the proof:\n\n```tactics\nimport Mathlib.Tactic\n\nimport ProblemExtraction\n\nproblem_file {\n  tags := [.NumberTheory]\n}\n\n/-!\n# International Mathematical Olympiad 2022, Problem 3\n\nLet k be a positive integer an